OL,6,FIf you regularly read about science in
OL,7,Fthe news, it's easy to end up
OL,8,Fmisinformed. Whether it's a newspaper
OL,9,Farticle whipping up a health scare (or
OL,10,Fpromoting a miracle cure) on the basis
OL,11,Fof a shoddy study, or a fabulously
OL,12,Fexciting "breakthrough" that you never
OL,13,Fhear of again, we've all ended up
OL,14,Fdisappointed by science news.
OL,16,FLast year was no exception. Every month
OL,17,Fbrought with it a science story that
OL,18,Fwas subject to hype, overstatement, or
OL,19,Fjust plain incorrect reporting ` often
OL,20,Faided and abetted by scientists
OL,21,Fthemselves.
OL,3,C5 things you can do to stop getting
OL,4,Ctricked by bad science writing in 2023
